summaries.short: Segments: Boston marathon head runs vax sites; youth mental health struggles during COVID; the toughest race on Earth; risky skiing deaths.
summaries.full: Real Sports profiles longtime Boston Marathon director Dave McGillivray, who now runs mass vaccination sites, then looks at the dramatic rise of mental health issues in young athletes amid COVID-19. Next, we head to Tennessee for "The Barkley," considered the toughest ultramarathon on the planet, before examining why this backcountry skiing season has been the deadliest yet.

titles.full: Real Sports Podcast Ep. 7: "Benched: Youth Mental Health Fallout"

summaries.short: Max Gershberg is joined by Kavitha Davidson to discuss her report on the emotional toll that a year without sports has taken on kids.
summaries.full: Max Gershberg is joined by Kavitha Davidson to discuss her report on the emotional toll that a year without sports has taken on kids.

summaries.short: With the pandemic leaving sports programs on the sidelines, many young athletes are displaying an alarming rise in mental health disorders.
summaries.full: With the pandemic leaving many sports programs on the sidelines, many young athletes are displaying an alarming rise in mental health disorders, including depression and anxiety.

titles.short: The Toughest Race on the Planet
titles.full: The Toughest Race on the Planet

summaries.short: Real Sports treks to rugged mountains in Tennessee to report on "The Barkley," one of the world's most challenging ultra-marathons.
summaries.full: Known as one of the world's most grueling races, "The Barkley" is a 100-mile running event in the mountains of Tennessee with 120,000 feet of elevation gains and descents in often-treacherous conditions. There's also a catch: you must complete the run in 60 hours. Mary Carillo chats with the man who started this incredibly challenging event, Lazarus Lake.

summaries.short: While backcountry skiing has seen record growth during the pandemic, dangerous conditions have made this season one of the deadliest ever.
summaries.full: While backcountry skiing has seen record growth during the pandemic, dangerous snow conditions have elevated the risk of avalanches, making this season one of the deadliest ever.

summaries.short: Longtime Boston Marathon race director Dave McGillivray has found a new purpose: overseeing four mass vaccination sites in Massachusetts.
summaries.full: With the Boston Marathon cancelled due to the pandemic, longtime race director Dave McGillivray has found a new purpose: overseeing operations at four mass vaccination sites in Massachusetts, where thousands of people are vaccinated every day.

titles.full: Real Sports Podcast Ep. 8: "The Fight Before the Fight"

summaries.short: Host Max Gershberg is joined by sports journalist and renowned mixed martial arts reporter Ariel Helwani to discuss the MMA culture.
summaries.full: Host Max Gershberg is joined by sports journalist and renowned mixed martial arts reporter Ariel Helwani to discuss MMA's brutal weight-cutting culture, its origins, and whether he sees reform coming anytime soon.

summaries.short: Segments: The world of mini-bull riding; female reporters expose sexual harassment; the ban on Olympic protests; amazing one-armed prodigy.
summaries.full: Segments: A look at the world of mini-bull riding where boys as young as eight years old ride bulls; female sports reporters continue to face sexual objectification and abuse; Bryant Gumbel heads up a virtual panel to discuss the International Olympic Committee’s prohibition of any kind of demonstration; former one-armed golf prodigy Tommy Morrissey is now dominating baseball.

summaries.short: Segments: NBA vet Jayson Williams' unique rehab; Paralympic superstar Oksana Masters; Cory Booker on college reform; bionic man Hugh Herr.
summaries.full: Segments: Troubled former NBA star Jayson Williams is running a rehab facility that uses outdoor adventure therapy; Oksana Masters has overcome immense trauma to become one of the most decorated Paralympic athletes ever; Bryant Gumbel leads a panel on college amateurism with Sen. Cory Booker and former NCAA investigator Tim Nevius; update on "bionic man" Hugh Herr.

titles.full: Real Sports Podcast Ep. 9: "Reporting While Female" with Andrea Kremer

summaries.short: Max Gershberg is joined by correspondent Andrea Kremer to discuss the longtime harassment female journalists have faced covering sports.
summaries.full: Host Max Gershberg is joined by correspondent Andrea Kremer to discuss the longtime harassment female journalists have faced covering sports and the impact #MeToo could have on making sports reporting a more accepting place for women.

summaries.short: Jon Frankel looks at the world of mini-bull riding where boys as young as eight years old ride bulls more than 10 times their size.
summaries.full: Bull riding is known as the most dangerous eight seconds in sports, but in the world of mini-bull riding, it’s all in a day’s work for boys as young as 8 years old as they hop aboard animals more than 10 times their size.

summaries.short: Forty years after gaining equal access to locker rooms, female sports reporters continue to face sexual objectification and abuse.
summaries.full: Sports journalism isn't supposed to be a hazardous profession, but for female reporters, working in this male-dominated industry can range from difficult to horrifying. Now some of those women are speaking out about what they say is a culture of objectification and sexual harassment.

summaries.short: Bryant Gumbel heads up this virtual panel to discuss the International Olympic Committee’s prohibition of any kind of demonstration.
summaries.full: Bryant Gumbel is joined by Tommie Smith, who famously raised a gloved fist on the podium at the 1968 Olympic Games, gold medal sprinter and long jumper Tianna Bartoletta, fencer Race Imboden and hammer thrower Gwendolyn Berry to discuss Rule 50 of the Olympic Charter, which prohibits demonstrations of any kind.

summaries.short: Tommy Morrissey, once a seven-year-old golf prodigy who was born with only one arm, has now started dominating in another sport: baseball.
summaries.full: In this update on Tommy Morrissey, the once seven-year-old golf prodigy who was born with only one arm, has now started dominating in another sport: baseball.

titles.full: Real Sports Podcast Ep. 10: "Why Black America Has Abandoned Baseball"

summaries.short: Max Gershberg and Doug Glanville look at Chris Rock's 2015 stand-up piece on why black baseball fans are an "endangered species."
summaries.full: Host Max Gershberg is joined by former Major League Baseball outfielder Doug Glanville to look back on Chris Rock's 2015 stand-up piece on why black baseball fans are considered an "endangered species."

summaries.short: Segments: Wall Street firm bets on baseball; IOC push to vaccinate athletes amid shortage; Olympic skateboarder Alexis Sablone; bike wars.
summaries.full: Segments: Former pitcher Michael Schwimer's private equity fund aimed at helping minor league players; the IOC's continued push for the Olympic Games at any cost; Meet Alexis Sablone, street skater extraordinaire and unlikely Olympic athlete; an update on the bicycling boom that erupted during the pandemic.

summaries.short: Former troubled NBA star Jayson Williams is helping others running a rehab facility that treats addiction with outdoor adventure therapy.
summaries.full: NBA veteran Jayson Williams has overcome a tortured past of addiction and has dedicated his life to helping save others--including a number of other former NBA players--with a South Florida rehab facility that uses outdoor adventure therapy like skydiving, wave running and scuba diving to treat addiction issues.

summaries.short: Despite physical challenges and a traumatic childhood, Oksana Masters has become one of the most decorated Paralympic athletes ever.
summaries.full: Oksana Masters was born with devastating birth defects after her mother was exposed to radioactive fallout in Chernobyl. But physical challenges and a traumatic childhood have not stopped her from becoming one of the most decorated and inspiring Paralympic athletes ever.

summaries.short: Hugh Herr lost both legs to frostbite but it didn't stop the rock climber and MIT professor from turning himself into a modern bionic man.
summaries.full: Hugh Herr may have lost both legs to frostbite but it didn't stop the accomplished rock climber and MIT professor from turning himself into a modern bionic man--and in the process, change what's possible for amputees and even able-bodied athletes looking to push the limits of what’s humanely possible.

summaries.short: Bryant Gumbel leads a panel on the current state of college amateurism with Sen. Cory Booker and former NCAA investigator Tim Nevius.
summaries.full: Bryant Gumbel leads a virtual panel on the current state of college amateurism with U.S. Senator Cory Booker (D-NJ) and former NCAA investigator Tim Nevius.

titles.full: Real Sports Podcast Ep. 5: "Bouncing Back" with Jayson Williams

summaries.short: Host Max Gershberg is joined by former NBA star Jayson Williams to discuss his adventure-based therapy program, "Rebound."
summaries.full: Host Max Gershberg is joined by former NBA star Jayson Williams to discuss his adventure-based therapy program, "Rebound," and how healing others suffering from addiction has helped him work through his own painful past.

titles.full: Real Sports Podcast Ep. 6: Going the Extra Mile: Remembering Dick Hoyt

summaries.short: Max Gershberg is joined by Boston Marathon director Dave McGillivray to reflect on the incredible life story of his late friend, Dick Hoyt.
summaries.full: Max Gershberg is joined by Boston Marathon director Dave McGillivray to reflect on the incredible life story of his late friend, Dick Hoyt.

summaries.short: Segments: The lack of Black NFL head coaches; Wim Hof's extreme cold water health claims; youth travel sports spreading COVID; Chess boom.
summaries.full: Segments: Veteran coaches of color including Mike Tomlin speak out about how and why they're not being viewed as the equal of their white peers; Wim "The Iceman" Hof's pioneering cold-water immersion and breathing techniques; Despite the pandemic, many high school and youth travel team sports continue to play on; Chess boomed in popularity during the pandemic.

titles.full: Real Sports Podcast Ep. 11: "Big League Advance"

summaries.short: Max Gershberg and Nick Dolin examine former MLB pitcher Michael Schwimer’s pioneering investment firm, Big League Advance.
summaries.full: Host Max Gershberg is joined by fellow Real Sports Producer Nick Dolin to examine former Major League Baseball pitcher Michael Schwimer’s pioneering investment firm, Big League Advance.

summaries.short: Former pitcher Michael Schwimer created a private equity fund aimed at helping minor league players who often barely earn minimum wage.
summaries.full: While baseball players earn vast amounts of money at the major league level, minor leaguers often struggle to make minimum wage. It’s a reality that former pitcher Michael Schwimer saw up close and why he created a unique private equity fund that pays minor league players in exchange for a percentage of their future baseball earnings.

summaries.short: Meet Alexis Sablone, street skater extraordinaire and unlikely Olympic athlete, headed to Tokyo to compete in the new skateboarding event.
summaries.full: Alexis Sablone is one of the best female skaters in the world and a medal-contender in the new sport of skateboarding at the upcoming Tokyo Games, despite being at odds with the idea of even being an Olympian.

summaries.short: While the pandemic continues to ravage many parts of the world, the IOC continues its relentless push for the Olympic Games at any cost.
summaries.full: While the pandemic continues to ravage many parts of the world, Real Sports examines the IOC’s practice of promoting the vaccination of thousands of young, healthy Olympic-bound athletes despite a global shortage.

summaries.short: Despite the bicycling boom that erupted during the pandemic, the streets of America have remained as dangerous as ever for cyclists.
summaries.full: While the COVID-19 pandemic brought the world to a stop, it set off a “bike boom” that actually triggered a global bike shortage. But while some efforts were made to accommodate bikers in America, the streets have remained as dangerous as ever for cyclists, particularly with traffic returning to pre-pandemic levels.

summaries.short: Host Max Gershberg is joined by correspondent David Scott to discuss the effort put forth by the IOC and Japan to host the 2021 Olympics.
summaries.full: Host Max Gershberg is joined by correspondent David Scott to discuss the effort put forth by the International Olympic Committee and Japan to host the 2021 Olympics.

summaries.short: Segments: Ex-NBA stars turned marijuana moguls; hunting contests to control wildlife; 10 year-old chess prodigy; paragliding for disabled.
summaries.full: Segments: Former NBA stars jump into the cannabis biz aiming to grow profits and help the Black community; with various wildlife populations out of control, some hunters are competing for cash prizes to curb unwanted animals; ten-year-old Nigerian refugee Tani Adewumi is a rising star in the world of chess; a paragliding outfit gives people who can’t walk the chance to fly.

summaries.short: Veteran coaches of color including Mike Tomlin speak out about how and why they're not being viewed as the equal of their white peers.
summaries.full: Despite stated promises of fairness and opportunity, there are still few black head coaches in the NFL - a fact that has left veteran coaches of color, including Mike Tomlin of the Pittsburgh Steelers, speaking out about how and why they're not being viewed or treated as the equal of their white peers.

summaries.short: How Wim "The Iceman" Hof's pioneering cold-water immersion and breathing techniques have enabled him to achieve amazing feats and health.
summaries.full: Wim "The Iceman" Hof loves the cold perhaps more than anyone on the planet. Jon Frankel explores how Hof's pioneering cold-water immersion and breathing techniques have enabled him to achieve amazing athletic feats and claims of remarkable health and wellness benefits.

summaries.short: Despite the pandemic, many high school and youth travel team sports continue to play on--and are contributing to the spread of the virus.
summaries.full: Despite the shutdown of almost all group gatherings amid the pandemic, many high school and youth travel team sports continue to play on--and are contributing to the spread of the virus.

summaries.short: Chess boomed in popularity this year as a hit TV show made the game cool while the pandemic drove millions inside and onto chess websites.
summaries.full: Online chess games, internet chess celebrities, and Netflix's The Queen's Gambit have led to a popularity explosion for the game amidst the pandemic. Soledad O'Brien revisits with chess revolutionary Rex Sinquefield, who built a chess empire in his hometown of St. Louis.

titles.full: Real Sports Podcast Ep. 3: "Black Coaches in the NFL"

summaries.short: Real Sports Podcast host Max Gershberg delves into Bryant Gumbel's report on the lack of Black head coaches in the NFL with Rod Graves.
summaries.full: Real Sports Podcast host Max Gershberg delves into Bryant Gumbel's report on the lack of Black head coaches in the NFL with guest Rod Graves, the Executive Director of The Fritz Pollard Alliance.

titles.full: Real Sports Podcast Ep. 4: "Reforming College Athletics"

summaries.short: Max Gershberg and Sen. Cory Booker discuss the NCAA's current amateurism model and Booker's bill, the College Athletes Bill of Rights.
summaries.full: Host Max Gershberg is joined by Senator from New Jersey Cory Booker to discuss the NCAA's current amateurism model and how his proposed bill, the College Athletes Bill of Rights, would change the way student-athletes are treated.

summaries.short: Segments: COVID 'long-haulers'; Minneapolis cop/coach faces challenges being 'Black and blue'; abuse allegations at Nike's track program.
summaries.full: Segments: A report on the stories of COVID-19 'long haulers,' athletes who continue to suffer debilitating symptoms months after having the virus; a black Minneapolis police officer coached North HS football to great success--and faced challenges in the wake of George Floyd's murder; a look inside Nike's elite track program in the wake of abuse allegations.

summaries.short: Former NBA stars are part of the new green gold rush of the legal cannabis industry, looking to grow profits and help the Black community.
summaries.full: Former NBA stars Al Harrington and Matt Barnes are part of the new green gold rush of the legal cannabis industry, looking to grow profits and help build investment and ownership opportunities in the Black community.

summaries.short: With various wildlife populations out of control across America, some hunters are now competing for cash prizes to curb unwanted animals.
summaries.full: With various animal populations growing out of control and causing damage across the country, hunting contests offering cash prizes have been organized to help curb unwanted wildlife. But in recent years, with pressure mounting from animal rights groups, some states have started banning these contests, while experts question their overall effectiveness.

summaries.short: Two years ago, 10 year-old Nigerian refugee Tani Adewumi lived in a homeless shelter. Today he is a rising star in the world of chess.
summaries.full: Tani Adewumi isn’t your typical ten-year-old. Instead of wanting to play in the NFL or NBA, he dreams about becoming the youngest player ever to become a Grand Master in chess. It would be a remarkable achievement, considering just two years ago, Tani and his family were living in a New York City homeless shelter after fleeing Boko Haram in their native Nigeria.

summaries.short: Project Airtime gives disabled athletes the chance to fly - offering them joy, exhilaration, and the opportunity to feel whole again.
summaries.full: In 2018, we first discovered Utah-based Project Airtime, an adaptive paragliding outfit founded by one-time extreme sportsman Chris Santacrocce. Disabled athlete Joe Stone has now brought Santacrocce’s mission to Jackson, Wy., where he’s established a Project Airtime outpost to spread the paragliding gospel and give others like him the chance to feel whole again.

titles.full: Real Sports Podcast Ep. 13: "Green Gold Rush" with Al Harrington

summaries.short: Host Max Gershberg is joined by former NBA player, and cannabis entrepreneur, Al Harrington.
summaries.full: Host Max Gershberg is joined by former NBA player, and cannabis entrepreneur, Al Harrington.

titles.full: Real Sports Podcast Ep. 14: "The Life of a Sports Agent"

summaries.short: Max Gershberg is joined by sports super agent Leigh Steinberg, who went from living the high life to falling into bankruptcy and addiction.
summaries.full: Host Max Gershberg is joined by sports super agent Leigh Steinberg, who went from living the high life to falling into bankruptcy and battling addiction to then rebuilding his life and returning to prominence as a top agent. Steinberg reflects on his journey from when Real Sports last spoke with him in 2012.

titles.full: Real Sports Podcast Ep. 1: "The Long Haul"

summaries.short: Max Gershberg and Mary Carillo dive into "The Long Haul" report to learn more about the long-lasting effects of COVID-19 on athletes.
summaries.full: The Real Sports Podcast kicks off its first episode by diving deeper into "The Long Haul" report featured on the January 26, 2021 episode of Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel. Host Max Gershberg is joined by correspondent Mary Carillo to learn more about the long-lasting effects of COVID-19 on athletes and why this story initially scared her.

summaries.short: A report on the stories of COVID-19 'long haulers,' athletes who continue to suffer debilitating symptoms months after having the virus.
summaries.full: Mary Carillo reports on the startling stories of COVID-19 'long haulers,' athletes who continue to suffer debilitating symptoms months after contracting the virus--and wonder if they'll ever be able to compete again.

summaries.short: A black Minneapolis police officer coached North HS football to great success--and faced challenges in the wake of George Floyd's murder.
summaries.full: Correspondent Jon Frankel heads to Minneapolis to report on how black police officer, Charles Adams, turned hometown North High School football into a perennial powerhouse and became a hero--until one night last May after George Floyd's murder when he was suddenly cast in a different role: enemy of the people.

summaries.short: A look inside Nike's elite track program in the wake of allegations by some members claiming they were mentally and physically abused.
summaries.full: Correspondent David Scott examines Nike's controversial 'Oregon Project' in the wake of allegations by some members of Nike's elite track program claiming they were mentally and physically abused.

titles.full: Real Sports Podcast Ep. 2: "Trump's Golf Reckoning"

summaries.short: Host Max Gershberg and golf journalist John Feinstein reflect on the April 2016 Real Sports story "Trumped."
summaries.full: The Real Sports Podcast looks back at the story, "Trumped," an updated report from the April 2016 episode of Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel. Host Max Gershberg is joined by golf journalist John Feinstein to bring us up to speed on former President Donald Trump's status in the golf world, and how the events at the Capitol prompted the PGA to cut ties with Trump--for now.
